This song always reminds me of when I was in APUSH after Trump first got elected (we were talking about his policies and how it'll affect the country and how it relates to previous administrations), and I was crying because I was extremely upset about what he might do. I mentioned that I was worried that he might try and force me out of my home and put me in a camp simply because I'm Native American (my specific tribe is very small and experiences lots of racism, even amongst other tribes). I wonder how my teacher and classmates feel when they also think of me crying that day and worrying about something they told me would never happen. For those who don't know, Native Americans are being targeted by the Trump administration. They are trying to pass a law that would overturn a 1924 law that made Native Americans legal citizens of the US. Since his inauguration ICE agents have been harassing Natives leaving reservations by asking for papers and trying to detain and arrest them.  With his aggressive anti-immigration laws and policies (sending (read: selling) those who can't be sent back to their home country to camps in other countries to be used as a labor force or sent to Guantanamo Bay (yes, the same one they use to torture suspected and convicted terrorists. The camp there is labeled as 'temporary', which given its bloodied history can easily like it to be a death camp in the making). Seeing as Native Americans are from North America and the administration's goal is to send (read: sell to El Salvador) out all illegal people in the country, where would we be sent? All five million plus Native Americans? What would happen to our land, the land that oil, logging, construction, and mining companies have been itching to get their hands on?  For anyone whose read this far and still doesn't believe me, there has already been multiple cases of legal citizens, and even veterans, being illegally detained by ICE, and in one notable case (Davino Watson), was essentially held hostage by ICE for three years and can't sue due to a legal loophole that ICE knowingly used against him. They don't care if you're actually a legal citizen or not, they care about if you look like one. All of this is for me to say to those who never thought that the Trump administration would do something so rancid, blatantly illegal, and fundamentally against human rights; are you ashamed for not seeing the writing on the wall as I, a then 16 year old, did?

She actually watched the Superbowl (I did not) and reported the performance was very well choreographed but did NOT understand anything Lamar actually SAID!  As a member of the hearing loss community, I can appreciate how hard it can be to receive a "message" that you cannot hear? ğŸ¤” The visuals were great and I imagine Kendrick (not knowing any of his music) was rapping some very profound words. However, most old white Americans (aka a good chunk of the Superbowl) are NOT familiar with hip hop and CANNOT appreciate what he is actually saying due to poor hearing ability! What a difference it might have made if Lamar has found a way to make sure his words were received LOUD and CLEAR... Subtitles on the tv at least? Not enough people talk about how damaging the fake â€œwhite cops kill black peopleâ€ narrative (which this video at least partly eludes to) was.  Stories that fit that narrative were cherry picked and brought to the masses, causing a snowball affect of confirmation bias that this was an exclusively white on black phenomenon. I remember people gradually quit thinking critically about what actually happened in those police killings because they saw the explicitly white on black trend as evidence enough of that white cops just like killing blacks.  It's a very destructive narrative because even if a neutral observation of all police shooting would show that it happens disproportionately to blacks (idk if it does or doesn't), that's a mile away from "it only happens to blacks". The George Floyd summer would probably not have happened (or at least be tolerated) if people like Tony Timpa had equal coverage.

In numerical terms, the operation is expressed as 1 + 1. When you add one to another one, the result is two, which can be represented numerically as "2". This operation is often one of the first arithmetic concepts taught in early education due to its simplicity and foundational role in more complex mathematical concepts. Visualizing one plus one can be as simple as imagining two individual apples being placed together in a basket; if you start with one apple and add another, you end up with two apples total. This concept applies universally across objects and scenarios. The principle of one plus one extends beyond numbers alone; it can be seen in various real-life applications. For example, combining one person with another person results in a pair. In essence, the idea of one plus one is a building block for understanding how quantities combine and grow, offering a straightforward yet crucial insight into the world of mathematics and arithmetic operations.

When I was younger, I didn't quite understand this video in the way it was meant to be understood. When I was a teenager (which was how old I was when this came out), I thought this video was just about how Black people are disproportionately affected by systemic issues in this country. Now, at the age of 23, rewatching this before the 2024 general election... I realize that this video is about the hypocrisy of consuming Black culture (which we all do to some extent through our media), giving superficial nods to Black artists who graciously expose us to their culture, and then us doing absolutely NOTHING to change the systemic brutalization of Black people. I'm grateful to all of the perspectives I've encountered that have helped me understand, even just a little bit, about how important it is to pay attention to things like this, and vote in a way that benefits us all, not just me.

One way of interpreting the video I guess is, that the way Gambino dances and sings about self centred and superficial things like his looks and how cool he is, while surrounded by gun violence, riots, and growing chaos, is basically a metaphor for how American culture focuses on superficial things while ignoring it's own collapse happening in the background. There's obviously a call out to gun violence, and the lyrics like 'Grandma told me get yo money, Black man (get yo money)' possibly pointing out how for many in the US, they're taught from an early age to just focus on themselves and surviving, getting money, often by any means. A lot of I guess you could say the lyrics also reference a lot of gangsta rap style lyrics where rappers pretend to be gangstas and boast about how 'bad' they are, and basically makes a mockery of how there's almost a bizarre sense of pride among those who have learnt to survive in a system that is obviously broken. There's probably 50 billion ways to interpret the video, but I think the most obvious interpretation is, the video says "This is America", and what it shows, isn't something to be proud of.

I remember turning 21, having just moved to DC for work, and this song coming out.  I was in the place I dreamed of living since my youth when this song came out. We had a tyrannical inflammatory President at the time. Every week if I was traveling for work there was a shooting or police brutality in the news, often somewhere nearby while traveling for work. Money was flowing because regulators were replaced by people like Ajit Pai who worked for Verizon and then became chairman of the FCC. There is an insane amount of corrupted and lobbied politics that occurred for years. Crypto scams and ideas that made no sense. This song for me is as to Trumps Presidency as was "Fortunate Son" by Creedance Clearwater was to the Vietnam war. I'll even add that people were so scared that American Horror Story made a season about extremist cults dedicated to the president at the time, since political voting parties were so polarized they seemed extreme from the outside. On January 4-6 racists gathered within 20 minutes of my house at the time and I had to tell my girlfriend not to leave the house since racists were in the hotels nearby and causing scenes where they went. On January 6 there was an actual riot at the Whitehouse as most of us know. When life imitates art. Riots with police/police brutality occurred in Portland Oregon.  I remember the statues being taken down from Richmond VA after BLM riots occured there as well, driving through and seeing the statue's bases spray painted over. Events like George Floyd and so many more following. This music video reminds me of all of it. I still have a mug that says "literally anyone sane 2020" and I remember seeing the same slogan in Pittsburgh on banners outside of houses. When I was in my sophomore year of Highschool roughly I remember someone drove a dodge Challenger through a peaceful protest in Charlottesville VA, and after that I never wanted a Dodge Challenger ever again. Then later in my life when I was in that DC area I visited Charlottesville and there were Nazi tattooed skinheads begging for money and it was the first time I had ever seen someone so openly racist. It gave my chills up through my spine like "we have to get out of here" and it was shocking to see such bold display of insanity. Watching it go full circle was shocking coming from small towns where I never really met a real racist.
I have to be in the right mood to watch this video because it's insanely powerful. But I've been coming back to it since he released it.
